---
title: Switch statement
---

The switch statement can select an option between multiple statements. It can be an alternative for an if/else if statement.

General format:

switch (expression) //integer
{                   
	case expression1: statement1;
  break;
	case expression2: statement2;
  break;
..........

	default:   statement3;
}


There are no limits to the number of cases.
When a case is not chosen, the switch statement will execute the default line.
Each case has to be separated by a break; statement.


Example:
int main()
{
char expression;

cout << "Enter letter A or B";
cin >> expression;

switch(expression)
{
  case 'A': cout << "You entered A.";
  break;
  case 'B': cout << "You entered B.";
  break;
  default: cout << "You did not enter A or B.";
}
return 0;
}




